SIMPLE: suspicion
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Suspicion
<hw>Sus*pi"cion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>suspecioun</ets>, OF. <ets>souspe⟦cced⟧on</ets>, F.
<ets>soup⟦cced⟧on</ets>, L. <ets>suspectio</ets> a looking up to, an
esteeming highly, suspicion, fr. <ets>suspicere</ets> to look up, to
esteem, to mistrust. The modern form <ets>suspicion</ets> in English and
French is in imitation of L. <ets>suspicio</ets> mistrust, suspicion.
See <er>Suspect</er>, and cf. <er>Suspicious</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of suspecting; the imagination or apprehension of the
existence of something (esp. something wrong or hurtful) without proof,
or upon very slight evidence, or upon no evidence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Suspicions</qex> among thoughts are like bats among birds,
they ever fly by twilight.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Slight degree; suggestion; hint.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The features are mild but expressive, with just a
<qex>suspicion</qex> . . . of saturnine or sarcastic humor.</q>
<rj><qau>A. W. Ward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Jealousy; distrust; mistrust; diffidence;
doubt.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suspicion</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Suspicion
<hw>Sus*pi"cion</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To view with suspicion; to
suspect; to doubt.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Low]</mark>
<rj><au>South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suspicious</ent>⟦br⟧
